<p>Eduardo Mendieta, professor of philosophy at Penn State University, has died.<span id="more-56025"></span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="size-full wp-image-56026 aligncenter" src="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/mendieta-eduardo-photo-1.png" alt="" width="400" height="300" srcset="https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/mendieta-eduardo-photo-1.png 400w, https://dailynous.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/12/mendieta-eduardo-photo-1-300x225.png 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px" /></p>
<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eduardo_Mendieta" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Professor Mendieta</a>, described by some as a &#8220;giant&#8221; in Latin American and Latinx philosophy, wrote on various topics in ethics, social and political philosophy, the human condition, animals, critical theory, and philosophy of race. He is the author of <a href="https://sunypress.edu/Books/G/Global-Fragments" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Global Fragments: Globalizations, Latinamericanisms, and Critical Theory</em></a> (2007) and <a href="https://www.bloomsbury.com/us/adventures-of-transcendental-philosophy-9798216303015/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Adventures of Transcendental Philosophy</em></a> (2002), among other works. His most recent book is <a href="https://library.oapen.org/handle/20.500.12657/91195" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Philosophical Animal: On Zoopoetics and Interspecies Cosmopolitanism</em></a> (2024).Â  You can learn more about his writings <a href="https://philpeople.org/profiles/eduardo-mendieta" target="_blank" rel="noopener">here</a>.</p>
<p>Mendieta joined the <a href="https://philosophy.la.psu.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Department of Philosophy</a> at Penn State in 2015. Prior to that, he was professor and chair of <a href="https://www.stonybrook.edu/philosophy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">philosophy at Stony Brook University</a>, where he had moved, in 2001, from the <a href="https://www.usfca.edu/arts-sciences/programs/undergraduate/philosophy" target="_blank" rel="noopener">University of San Francisco</a>. He earned his PhD in philosophy at <a href="https://www.newschool.edu/nssr/philosophy/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The New School for Social Research</a>, an MA from <a href="https://utsnyc.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Union Theological Seminary</a>, and his undergraduate degree in philosophy from <a href="https://philosophy.rutgers.edu/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Rutgers University</a>.</p>
<p>He died on December 17th, 2025 from cancer.</p>
[via Alex Guerrero]<p>The post <a href="https://dailynous.com/2025/12/29/eduardo-mendieta-1963-2025/">Eduardo Mendieta (1963-2025)</a> first appeared on <a href="https://dailynous.com">Daily Nous</a>.</p>